and Foucault: A Reading of Dawn -- t17. Gapping the Subject: Nietzsche and Derrida -- t18. Questioning Introspection: Nietzsche and Wittgenstein on “The Peculiar Grammar of the Word ‘I’” -- t19. Subjects as Temporal Clues to Orientation: Nietzsche and Luhmann on Subjectivity -- t20. Three Senses of Selfless Consciousness: Nietzsche and Dennett on Mind, Language and Body -- t21. Nietzsche on the Embodiment of Mind and Self -- t22. Self-Knowledge, Genealogy, Evolution -- t23. Moralities Are a Sign-Language of the Affects -- t24. Nietzsche on Consciousness, Unity, and the Self -- t25. Nietzsche’s Socio-Physiology of the Self -- t26. The Expressivist Nietzsche -- tComplete Bibliography -- tList of Contributors/Affiliations -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNietzsche's critique of the modern subject is often presented as a radical break with modern philosophy and associated with the so-called ‘death of the subject’ in 20th century philosophy. But Nietzsche claimed to be a ‘psychologist’ who was trying to open up the path for ‘new versions and sophistications of the soul hypothesis.’ Although there is no doubt that Nietzsche gave expression to a fundamental crisis of the modern conception of subjectivity (both from a theoretical and from a practical-existential perspective), it is open to debate whether he wanted to abandon the very idea of subjectivity or only to pose the problem of subjectivity in new terms.The volume includes 26 articles by top Nietzsche scholars. The chapters in Part I, “Tradition and Context”, deal with the relationship between Nietzsche's views on subjectivity and modern philosophy, as well as with the late 19th century context in which his thought emerged; Part II, “The Crisis of the Subject”, examines the impact of Nietzsche's critique of the subject on 20th century philosophy, from Freud to Heidegger to Dennett, but also in such authors as Deleuze, Foucault, Derrida, or Luhmann; Part III, “Current Debates - From Embodiment and Consciousness to Agency”, shows that the way in which Nietzsche engaged with such themes as the self, agency, consciousness, embodiment and self-knowledge makes his thought highly relevant for philosophy today, especially for philosophy of mind and ethics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Jun 2020) 0aKnowledge, Theory of. 0aSubjectivity. 4aBewusstsein. 4aEmbodiment, self, agency, consciousness. 4aEmbodiment. 4aKrise des Subjekts. 4aSelbst. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / General.2bisacsh1 aConstâncio, João, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMayer Branco, Maria João, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRyan, Bartholomew, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2015z9783110438680oZDB-23-DPH0 cEPUBz97831104084090 cprintz978311040812640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110408201423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9783110408201.jpg  a978-3-11-070098-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2015  aZDB-23-DPHb2015